<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 92 / Commodities (Week in the Markets): Aluminium slide dents
recovery hopes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD MOONEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOPES THAT the recent strength of the aluminium and nickel markets might
augur a world economic recovery were dented this week when prices of both
metals fell sharply.
Aluminium buyers, especially in the Far East, were still in full cry during
the early part of the week and on Tuesday the London Metal Exchange cash
price closed at a 5 1/2 -month high of Dollars 1,274 a tonne. But the
failure of the three months position, which closed that day at Dollars
1,298.50 a tonne, to push on through the psychologically important Dollars
1,300 barrier signalled a change of sentiment and Far Eastern traders began
to take their profits.
As the cash price retreated to Dollars 1,221.50 a tonne at yesterday's
close, down Dollars 28 on the week, dealers explained that the earlier
sustained rise had created an 'overbought' market and a technical correction
was overdue.
The rise in LME warehouse stocks of aluminium continued - net deliveries
amounted to 10,025 tonnes this week, taking the total to a record 1,055,875
tonnes - but the market appears to have become inured to this factor.
Dealers noted yesterday that deliveries into the exchange's US warehouses
had slowed to a trickle, keeping alive hopes that there was some improvement
in American demand. But there was concern about a 1,500-tonne shipment into
a Japanese warehouse.
The nickel market's Dollars 690 upsurge since the start of this year had
already run into stiff resistance at the end of last week, when the three
months price failed to pass the Dollars 8,000-a-tonne mark. And this week
saw a substantial retreat as the disappearance of recent influential buying
allowed the negative fundamental situation to come to the fore. The
bearishness of fundamentals was highlighted by a further 1,392-tonne rise in
LME stocks to 17,916 tonnes, the highest level since September 1984. Dealers
thought this week's rise largely reflected Russian deliveries into LME
warehouses, and they said more was expected from that quarter.
Another factor weighing on the nickel market was the prospect of a strike in
the German steel industry, which it was feared would reduce demand from
nickel's key end-use sector. But even before it was announced yesterday that
steel workers in the IG Metall union had voted overwhelmingly in favour of
striking in support of their 10.5 per cent pay claim the threat was
beginning to lose its market potency. Dealers explained that the impact of a
strike had already been discounted in this week's price fall and that, in
any case, the overall supply/demand balance was not likely to be much
affected because lost German output was likely to be made up by other
European producers.
The cash nickel price lost an early gain after the result of the strike vote
was announced, finishing unchanged on the day at Dollars 7,665 a tonne, down
Dollars 200 on the week.
Zinc prices were also in retreat, as fears of a technical squeeze receded.
The cash price fell Dollars 23.50 to Dollars 1,159 a tonne, and its premium
over the three months price narrowed from Dollars 17 to Dollars 5.75 a tonne
at one point, although it widened again yesterday to Dollars 13 a tonne.
The week's biggest base metals rises were in the copper market, where the
cash quotation gained Pounds 26.50 to Pounds 1,220.50 a tonne - but most of
that reflected sterling's decline against the dollar.
Also supportive of the copper market was the threat strike by Chilean miners
over a plan for Codelco, the state-owned metals group, to grant controlling
stakes in joint ventures to private companies. The company said, however, it
was confident that a stoppage was 'highly improbable'.
At the London Futures and Options Exchange the March robusta coffee price
slid by another Pounds 61 to Pounds 505 a tonne. Dealers said sentiment was
affected by news that Brazil, the biggest producer, had no market
stabilisation proposals to put before next week's meeting of the
International Coffee Organisation and that the National Coffee Growers'
Federation of Colombia, the second biggest producer, was not even sending a
delegation. The meetings will be attended instead by the federation's
permanent representative in London.
Coffee's weakness was also influenced by the evaporation of squeeze fears on
the expiring January position, which went off the board quietly yesterday at
a small discount to the March contract, now the only remaining sterling
position.
