<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 92 / Money Markets: UK rates steady
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON LONDON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK money market ended the week facing a sizable liquidity shortage
following several days during which easier conditions had prevailed, writes
Simon London.
The Bank of England forecast a liquidity shortage of Pounds 1.2bn early in
the session, revised up to Pounds 1.3bn. As has been the pattern this week,
maturing treasury bills and assistance were the main components of the
shortage, draining Pounds 1.18bn from the market.
However, there was no early rush for funding and in early assistance the
Bank of England injected just Pounds 386m. The Bank purchased bills for
resale to the market at 10 7/16 per cent on February 17 and 18, switching
the repurchase dates from February 12 and 13 seen earlier in the week.
Later in the morning session a further Pounds 151m was purchased for resale
on the same terms. In the afternoon the bulk of the remaining shortage was
taken out, through the outright purchase of Pounds 704m band 1 bank bills at
10 7/16 per cent.
Late assistance of Pounds 75m bought the total liquidity injection for the
day to Pounds 1.316bn.
The unsecured overnight money rate was steady at around 11 per cent for most
of the morning but fell back to close at 10 3/4 -  5/8 per cent.
Longer rates were little changed. Three month interbank funds traded at 10
9/16 - per cent from 10 3/4 -  5/8 per cent on Thursday; one month interbank
money closed at 10 3/4 -  5/8 per cent.
The March short sterling contract on the London International Financial
Futures Exchange lost ground during the day and closed at 89.67. In mid-week
the contract had traded as high as 89.82.
In Frankfurt, call money traded up to 9.75 per cent, the same level as the
Lombard rate, the Bundesbank's emergency funding rate for financial
institutions.
The authorities injected funds at 9.7 per cent, transfering funds held on
deposit for public sector bodies, in an effort to relieve the the shortage.
The squeeze this week was sparked by pension payments draining cash from
banks and heavy funding towards the end of the month.
The pressure was evidenced by a surge in borrowing at the Lombard rate.
Financial institutions' Lombard borrowings reached DM7.1bn on Thursday,
having been static at under DM1bn for most of the month.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
