<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Good blue chip quarterly
results push Dow ahead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
GOOD quarterly results from a few big blue chip corporations lifted share
prices on US stock markets yesterday, as investors continued to digest the
implications of the new budget package and comments by the chairman of the
Federal Reserve about the state of the economy writes Patrick Harverson in
New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average ended 19.90 firmer at 3,244.86, its high
for the day. The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index improved
1.28 to 411.62, while the Nasdaq composite of over-the-counter stocks
advanced 5.06 to 621.37. New York Stock Exchange turnover amounted to 195m
shares.
The sharp fall in prices on Wednesday was triggered by hints from Mr Alan
Greenspan, the Fed chairman, that because the economy was steadily
recovering it was unlikely that fresh interest rate cuts would be needed to
stimulate growth. Mr Greenspan did say, however, that policy would be eased
if economic indicators suggested that further stimulus was required, and in
light of yesterday's bad economic news - a bigger than expected fall in
December durable goods orders and a 24,000 rise in weekly jobless claims -
investors' hopes for more rate red-uctions were briefly revived.
Among individual issues, three Dow contituent stocks gained good ground on
positive fourth-quarter earnings reports. Coca-Cola jumped Dollars 5 5/8 to
Dollars 77 1/8 , Boeing Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars 52 3/4 and McDonald's
Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 44 1/4 .
Dow Chemical rose Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 54 3/8 in spite of news of a
fourth-quarter loss of Dollars 92m, incurred because of a one-off Dollars
370m charge to cover asset write-offs and write-downs related to a recent
retrenchment in the company's operations. Investors were cheered by the
company's forecast of a return to profitability in 1992.
Airline issues were in the news. UAL forged ahead Dollars 5 1/4 to Dollars
144 1/2 after the company, as it had warned, announced its biggest ever
quarterly loss, a Dollars 10.69 a share deficit for the final three months
of 1991. UAL also revealed a Dollars 130m charge and plans to cut capital
spending by Dollars 2bn over the next three years.
Kellogg advanced Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 57 7/8 on news that Merrill Lynch,
the big broking house, had upgraded its long-term investment rating for the
food company's stock to 'very attractive', citing strong volume and margin
prospects. The recovery in Kellogg follows the sale on Wednesday by a
Boston-based money manager of his entire 1.1m-share stake.
On the over-the-counter market, Immunex jumped Dollars 5 3/8 to Dollars 62
after entering an agreement with Bristol-Myers Squibb (up Dollars 5/8 at
Dollars 80 3/8 ) to develop and market cancer therapeutics.
Canada
TORONTO finished on a modestly firmer note after fairly heavy trading. The
composite index gained 7.2 at 3,605.8, while rises exceeded declines by 316
to 245 after volume of 31.2m shares.
Canadian Turbo, up 65 cents at CDollars 3.30, said it has signed a letter of
intent with private concern Pay Less Holdings under which Pay Less would buy
most of Turbo's common shares for CDollars 3.96 apiece.
</TEXT>
