<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 92 / International Company News: Job-cutting charge hits Xerox
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
XEROX, the US document processing group, yesterday reported a 61 per cent
drop in fourth-quarter net income as it took a Dollars 175m pre-tax charge
against earnings to cover the cost of cutting 2,500 white-collar jobs.
The group reported net income of Dollars 91m, or 73 cents a share, compared
with Dollars 235m, or Dollars 2.27, in the same period of 1990. Last year's
figures included a Dollars 50m gain from the sale of its South Pacific
operations and Dollars 12m of losses from discontinued operations.
Revenues in the latest quarter dipped from Dollars 5bn to Dollars 4.9bn.
Xerox announced the Dollars 175m charge in December, saying it would
eliminate the jobs to create a more efficient, flatter, customer-responsive
organisation.
Revenues from its document processing business increased 3 per cent in the
fourth quarter, compared with 1990, excluding the South Pacific sale and
currency translations.
Fourth-quarter income was Dollars 188m, against Dollars 180m, excluding
special items. The group's insurance and other financial service operations
produced fourth-quarter earnings of Dollars 47m, down from Dollars 68m a
year ago.
For 1991, Xerox reported net income of Dollars 454m, or 3.91 a share,
compared with Dollars 235m, or Dollars 2.27 a share in 1990. Revenues
totalled Dollars 17.8bn, compared with Dollars 18bn the previous year.
Mr Paul Allaire, chairman, said Xerox had become a more customer-responsive
organisation in 1991. It had also increased market share as sales of
lower-end, less expensive office equipment continued to show good growth
throughout the year. However, the weak economy had hit sales of higher-end
products to larger customers.
He said that despite a weak property and casualty insurance market, profits
from financial services had been relatively stable.
</TEXT>
