<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JOHNSON &amp; Johnson, the leading healthcare products manufacturer, yesterday
turned in a 15 per cent increase in underlying 1991 earnings, led by strong
sales growth in its pharmaceutical business, and an expanded
over-the-counter products line.
Net income in the fourth quarter rose about 18 per cent to Dollars 274m, or
83 cents a share, from Dollars 232m, or 70 cents, a year earlier. Sales grew
nearly 13 per cent to Dollars 3.15bn from Dollars 2.79bn.
Stripping out the impact of currency exchange rates, the company said sales
increased 15 per cent in the quarter. About half of Johnson &amp; Johnson's
revenues come from outside the US.
For the year, the company had record earnings of Dollars 1.46bn, or Dollars
4.39 a share, on record sales of Dollars 12.45bn. In 1990, it earned Dollars
1.27bn, or Dollars 3.81, excluding non-recurring first-quarter charges of
Dollars 125m, or 38 cents. Sales were Dollars 11.23bn.
The company increased its spending on research and development by 17.5 per
cent in 1991, to almost Dollars 1bn. Mr Ralph Larsen, chairman and chief
executive, said more than 25 per cent of sales came from products introduced
in the past five years.
The company's consumer products operations had US sales of Dollars 2.46bn in
1991, up 17.8 per cent. International sales were flat at Dollars 2.12bn.
Johnson &amp; Johnson's pharmaceuticals segment performed better than consumer
products overseas, bringing in sales of Dollars 2.26bn, up 13.9 per cent in
the year. Domestic pharmaceutical sales advanced 16.4 per cent to Dollars
1.53bn.
