The workforce has been cut from 1,768 at end-March last year to 1,496 by the
end of December.
The company, which has been reducing its dependence on the defence market
during the past four years by developing its civil aerospace and electronic
component distribution businesses, said it had suffered from the combined
effects of the slump in civil aviation and the reduction in military
spending.
Turnover in the first half fell from Pounds 44m to Pounds 40m.
After accounting for some 64 per cent of total sales for the year to
end-March 1988, the contribution of defence activities has declined to 29
per cent of total sales for the 12 months ending September 1991.
It is expected to continue declining to about 20 per cent of total sales.
The company said its order book, which had fallen very sharply as a result
of the Gulf war and the recession, had recovered strongly in recent months.
Interest costs rose to Pounds 1.49m (Pounds 1.05m) in the half-year to
September. But borrowings peaked in October with gearing of more than 70 per
cent and were now on a downward trend.
The interim dividend is being maintained at 0.85p. Losses per share emerged
at 2.6p (earnings of 3.9p).
