<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Government fights to recover on VAT
 -Taxation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday escalated its offensive over the government's plans for
value added tax by seeking to highlight inconsistencies in prime minister
John Major's statements on the subject.
Using remarks made by Mr Major last April, the opposition tried to cast
doubt on his apparent pledge earlier this week not to implement further VAT
increases.
It later appeared to be unwittingly assisted in its aims when Mr John
MacGregor, leader of the Commons, reasserted Conservative commitment to the
notion of indirect taxation.
Mr MacGregor said the Tory-engineered shift from direct to indirect taxation
was 'absolutely right' because it enabled more people to spend money as they
wished to spend it.
'That is the policy we have consistently pursued, with the result that
direct taxes have come substantially down,' he said.
In an exceptionally rowdy Commons, Mr Roy Hattersley, deputising for Mr Neil
Kinnock, the Labour leader, opened by inquiring whether Mr Major's remarks
on Tuesday constituted a 'categorical assurance' that the VAT rate would not
rise.
If it was, he asked, how did that assurance square with Mr Major's statement
made last April 6 that 'no honest government could give a categorical
assurance that they would not increase VAT - no government ever has and no
government ever will.' Was Mr Major telling the truth 'last Tuesday or last
April?'
Mr MacGregor, standing in for the absent Mr Major, said the prime minister's
remarks on Tuesday had made the position 'absolutely clear.'
Mr Major had stated then there would be no VAT increase. The government had
published its spending plans and did not need a VAT rise to meet them.
He said this contrasted with Labour's position, which involved 'high
spending policies and is all over the place in deciding how it intends to
finance them.'
Mr Hattersley retorted by maintaining that Mr MacGregor lacked either the
courage or the authority to say whether the prime minister's pledge was
categorical or represented a promise he had no intention of keeping.
Mr Peter Kilfoyle, (Lab Walton) asked by how much VAT had risen since the
Tories entered office in 1979.
</TEXT>
