<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Lib Dems set out plan for Scots PR
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LIBERAL Democrats yesterday moved to distance themselves from Labour's
endorsement of proportional representation for its proposed Scottish
parliament, emphasising their preference for the single transferable vote
form of PR, David Owen writes.
The party also criticised Tory suggestions that Scotland faced a choice
between the union and full-blown independence. Mr Charles Kennedy, Liberal
Democrat president (above, left), described the stance as 'a very reckless
game'.
He suggested that political expediency might have motivated Labour's
plumping for the alternative member electoral system of PR. There was
concern that Labour's proposals might convert a minority Scottish vote to a
permanent Labour majority in Scotland, according to Mr Malcolm Bruce, the
Scottish Liberal Democrat leader (above, right).
The party also differed from Labour in admitting there was a case for
reviewing Scottish representation at Westminster 'once a Scottish parliament
with the powers we want is up and running'. Under the single transferable
vote, the electorate ranks candidates in order of preference - an
arrangement favoured by the Liberal Democrats for putting power in the hands
of voters as opposed to parties.
Under the additional member format, voters cast two votes - one for an
individual constituency candidate, as at present, and another for a party.
Labour yesterday denied that its motives were impure, saying it preferred
the additional member approach because it maintained a constituency link and
'topped up' the present first-past-the-post system.
</TEXT>
