<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Labour highlights southern
marginals - Housing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MARGINAL seats in the south of England were targeted yesterday by Labour in
a move to bring home to voters the effects of the Conservatives' policy on
house prices over the past four years.
Publishing a survey of house prices in 30 towns, Mr Bryan Gould, the shadow
environment secretary, said it showed 'there is rightly a very substantial
feel-bad factor running right through the very marginal seats that the
Tories are desperate to defend'.
Labour highlighted the fall in house prices in Mr John Major's Huntingdon
constituency and Mr Norman Lamont's Kingston seat since the end of 1987 - by
28 per cent and 19 per cent in cash terms.
The opposition offensive marks a renewed effort by Labour to point up the
difficulties faced by people in the south-east under the Tories, after a
Tory onslaught on the impact of Labour's tax plans on earners in London and
the south-east.
It also comes after Labour's national executive committee approved plans for
an elected, strategic authority for London.
Other areas where Labour highlighted the difficulties of homeowners were the
north-west and the Midlands, which saw rises of more than 40 per cent in the
numbers of court repossession orders made in 1991, and which contain a
number of marginal Tory seats.
</TEXT>
