</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 92 / Carsberg renews quest to curb monopoly: Oftel's proposals
for BT
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES LEADBEATER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SINCE 1984, when BT was privatised, Sir Bryan Carsberg, the departing
director-general of Oftel, has overseen a sweeping extension of price
controls on the privatised telecommunications operator.
At first, the watchdog covered services that provided half BT's revenues. It
now covers services that account for almost 70 per cent of BT revenue.
If BT hoped it would escape some of this regulation in the next few years as
competitors enter its market, encouraged by the government's liberalisation
of the telecommunications market last year, it will be disappointed.
It seems likely that as Sir Bryan departs this summer for his new job as
director-general at the Office of Fair Trading, he will leave behind an even
more extensive system of regulation.
According to an Oftel consultative document, published yesterday, on
proposals to renew price controls on BT from the middle of next year, the
case for regulation is undiminished.
Although BT may face growing competition in some areas of business services,
it is likely to retain an overwhelming monopoly in most sectors of the
market for the foreseeable future. In the absence of competition, regulation
is needed to prevent BT exploiting its monopoly power.
The document suggests three possible forms of regulation: a direct limit on
BT's profits; continuation of the price cap introduced in 1984; and a
profit-sharing arrangement that would ensure that the company shared any
unforeseen excess profits with its customers.
Oftel is firmly in favour of maintaining the current price-capping formula,
which limits BT's price increases to an amount less than the annual retail
price index, the so-called 'RPI - X' formula.
It says that, in spite of its drawbacks, the RPI is the most transparent
index to use, rather than BT's input prices or a special basket of
telecommunications prices.
The main issue to be decided by the review will be the value of 'X' in the
formula, which at present limits price increases to the RPI less 6.25 per
cent.
The document says the cap should continue to cover prices for local,
long-distance and international calls as well as private circuits.
Regulation should be extended to cover the rental price of hard-wire
handsets and might apply to new services such as call forwarding and call
barring, it says.
Oftel is seeking views on whether the price controls should cover an overall
basket of services or whether individual services, such as international
calls, should have special caps. It rejects the idea of a one-off reduction
in charges.
Sir Bryan recommends that the next price cap should last between four to
five years, the length of the previous two caps.
The document raises the possibility of linking quality-of-service targets to
the price controls, particularly where the quality of the network as a whole
is at issue. Oftel has no statutory powers relating to BT's quality of
service, although since 1987 BT has been forced to publish
quality-of-service reports.
It suggests that the present compensation scheme is the best way to deal
with customer complaints about poor quality.
Sir Bryan will consider whether BT should be required to publish its
accounts on a current-cost basis, which would reflect the high costs faced
by its competitors in installing modern telecommunications networks.
The drawback to that would be that it would allow BT to charge higher
prices, although it may also encourage competition by reflecting the real
costs of installing equipment.
The document casts doubt on the merit of controls on particular costs, such
as BT's investment expenditure.
It will review the adequacy of traditional measures of BT's productivity,
such as unit costs and the number of people employed per exchange line.
Those measures will be central to Oftel's judgment of the scope BT has to
cut costs, and its likely profits in the next few years - and therefore how
tightly the cap should be set.
The other main issue to be covered by the review is the flexibility and
structure of BT's tariffs, particularly the balance between prices for
installing lines and making calls, between prices for calls at peak and
cheap-rate times of day, and the size of local telephone districts.
Oftel favours an extension of the low-user scheme, which is designed to
compensate those on low incomes who might be affected by BT's moves to
rebalance its prices by raising line rentals and cutting call charges.
It will consider whether that scheme, which covers between 1.5m and 2m
customers, should be extended to a further group of customers, defined as
those whose telephone bills are significantly below the median.
The review will also examine whether BT should be obliged to provide a
recently developed talking terminal service which allows deaf people to use
the telephone.
After considering responses, Oftel will seek to negotiate a formula with BT.
If that fails, the issue will be referred to the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission.
Responses to the paper, The Regulation of BT's Prices, should be submitted
to Oftel, Room 229, Export House, 50 Ludgate Hill, London EC4M 7JJ. They
should arrive by Friday March 27.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
