<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 92 / Regulator relies on price cap to maintain control
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGO DIXON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BEST way of regulating BT's prices is by a price cap rather than by
controlling the telecommunications company's profits directly, Oftel, the
industry regulator, made clear yesterday.
Sir Bryan Carsberg, Oftel's director-general, also said, however, that
profits had to play an important part in deciding the appropriate price cap.
The main consideration was to set a cap that would lead to BT's making
'reasonable' profits if it achieved likely levels of efficiency.
Unlike previous price reviews, Oftel will be conducting this one mainly in
the open. In particular, it is making explicit what it means by reasonable
profits, has disclosed how BT's actual profits have diverged from its
forecasts, and has published disaggregated profits of the company's
different services for the first time.
Oftel says that in judging reasonableness, profits as a proportion of
capital employed should be weighed against the company's 'cost of capital' -
what it must pay to raise finance. That is the level of profitability that a
company in a competitive market would expect to earn.
Oftel uses two measures for cost of capital. The first is a calculation of
how much BT would have to pay to raise funds through a mixture of debt and
equity, taking into account the fact that its business is less risky than
most of the rest of British industry.
The second is an attempt to judge what rate of return investors are looking
at by comparing the company's share price with expectations of future
dividends.
Ideally, Oftel would do all those calculations on a current-cost -
inflation-adjusted - basis, but it has to rely on BT's conventional
historic-cost accounts.
On that basis Oftel calculates that a reasonable rate of return is 17 per
cent to 20 per cent for BT's regulated services. That is not directly
comparable with BT's reported return on capital because the figures cover
all its business.
Oftel calculates that in 1990-91 BT's return on regulated business was 25.4
per cent, compared with its expectations of 18 per cent when the last
comprehensive price review was conducted four years ago.
The implication is that BT's profitability is about 40 per cent higher than
expected. Another way of judging BT's profits is to compare them with those
of other companies (see table).
According to Oftel's document 'comparisons made on this basis suggest that
BT's returns are currently above average'. That conclusion is consistent
with an analysis of BT's profits last year by the Financial Times and Robert
Fleming Securities, the stockbroker.
Oftel's document explains how BT's profits diverged from expectations. The
main reason was that international call charges were not initially
regulated. If those are removed, the return on BT's regulated businesses was
only 20 per cent in 1990-91.
A tighter price cap, requiring BT to cut the average level of prices by 6.25
per cent after inflation, came into effect in September and is intended to
correct that.
Sir Bryan made clear that the decision on the new price cap would have to
take into account expectations of how effective the current price cap would
be in reducing BT's profitability.
The fall in BT's quarterly profits, announced yesterday, is evidence that
the tighter cap is having some effect. But other factors were also
responsible, in particular the weak economic climate and growing
competition.
The breakdown of profits for each of BT's main services supports the
company's case that it loses money in supplying telephone lines to
residential and business customers. It also shows BT is earning very high
profits on international and domestic long-distance calls.
It does not support BT's contention that the situation is deteriorating. Its
loss on residential line rentals as a percentage of capital employed fell to
11.8 per cent in 1990-91 from 14.3 per cent in 1989-90.
So the jury would still seem to be out on whether BT should be given greater
flexibility to increase rental charges - something likely to be one of the
most contentious features of the review.
