<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): Councils back wider pension scheme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE THAN 200,000 part-time workers in local government are likely to win
the right to join a pension scheme after local-authority associations agreed
to back a union claim that they should be admitted.
The decision by the associations representing county, metropolitan and
district authorities follows years of argument by the unions that the Local
Government Superannuation Scheme is discriminatory because it is not open to
council staff who work fewer than 15 hours a week.
Most part-time workers in local government are women.
The council associations are to write to the Department of the Environment
advising that the rules should be changed. Approval is expected to be given
because a similar change was made recently in health service pension
schemes.
Separately, local-government unions claimed a breakthrough in their campaign
for shorter hours when Kirkcaldy council, in east Scotland, agreed to a
36-hour week for 880 manual workers. The agreement to reduce hours from 39 a
week is one of the first to be negotiated at a UK local authority since
employers agreed as part of last year's national pay deal that they would
negotiate to introduce a 37-hour week by January 1994.
Measures to make it self-financing might include the introduction of monthly
rather than weekly pay.
The council associations' move on pensions was welcomed by Mr Donald
Macgregor, national officer at the GMB general union. He said it would
benefit thousands of council employees. 'It means that our members are on
the road to being treated with the respect they deserve.'
Local authorities have resisted the inclusion of part-timers in the pension
scheme partly because of cost implications. However, many councils believe
that maintaining the status quo is unfair. Some are also doubtful whether it
will increase costs because they believe many part-timers will choose not to
join the pension scheme.
One reason is that any pension could affect social security benefits after
retirement.
The Tate Gallery, the British Museum and the main part of the British
Library will be closed to the public today as London civil servants stage a
one-day strike over pay.
Jobcentres, unemployment benefit offices, the passport office and ministries
will also be affected by the strike called by the CPSA and NUCPS Civil
Service unions in protest against the government's refusal to raise London
weighting.
Union members will also picket the entrance to Downing Street, which
includes the home of the chancellor of the exchequer, who is responsible for
Civil Service pay.
</TEXT>
