<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): Profit-linked pay plans double to
3,000 in year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of companies with profit-related pay schemes more than doubled to
almost 3,000 last year, according to figures released by the Inland Revenue
yesterday.
The number of individual employees enrolled in schemes rose to nearly
600,000.
Profit-related pay schemes, which were introduced in 1987, offer tax relief
to employees up to a certain proportion of their salary. The number of
companies with schemes rose to 2,949 in the 12 months to last December,
compared with 1,233 a year earlier. The number of employees covered rose
from 263,400 to 581,000.
The number of employees covered by schemes still represents only 2 per cent
of the British working population.
Much of the increase took place in the last quarter of 1991, which the
Revenue said reflected attempts to register before the beginning of the new
tax year in April.
Mr John Maples, economic secretary to the Treasury, said the figures
reflected the doubling of tax relief for schemes announced in the 1991
Budget and they represented a 'major boost' to the idea of profit-related
pay.
Ms Jenny Davenport, head of employee relations and communications at the
Industrial Society, said: 'Performance-related pay is a bit of a
performance. It's a good thing but not terribly relevant.'
She said the limited level of tax relief offered under the scheme, the delay
before relief was paid and the bureaucracy involved in administering the
scheme explained why adoption rates were not higher.
Profit schemes have to cover 80 per cent of the employees in a company and
use a complex formula to fix payments.
</TEXT>
