FT  31 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): Tea break loss brings widespread
protests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LOSS of a Friday morning tea break has provoked unrest among engineering
construction workers at several sites, including Grangemouth in Scotland and
Sizewell in Suffolk.
The break was scrapped as part of a cut in working hours agreed with unions.
However, some workers may take their break today in protest, in spite of the
agreement.
Reductions in the working week have been achieved widely in the engineering
and building industries, partly by phasing out tea breaks.
National officials from the AEU and EETPU engineering unions and the GMB,
MSF and TGWU general unions met yesterday in an attempt to quell the unrest.
Earlier this week 3,000 workers stopped work for half a day at two oil
refinery sites in Grange-mouth.
There have also been protests involving a total of up to 6,000 workers at
the Sizewell nuclear power station, the Shell Haven oil refinery in Essex,
two power station sites at Killingholme, Humberside, and at one of the sites
at the St Fergus gas-processing plant in Grampian, according to Construction
News, the trade newspaper.
The employers confirmed yesterday that there had been a walk-out at
Grangemouth but said working had been resumed according to the agreement
that took effect on January 6.
Mr John Porter, chief executive of the National Engineering Construction
Employers' Association, said the 'vast majority' of sites had accepted the
new terms. He added that there were still matters to be resolved at Sizewell
and at British Nuclear Fuels' Sellafield site in Cumbria.
At those two sites some workers already worked a shorter day on Fridays, so
breaks were having to be cut from long shifts during the week, he said.
The agreement on reduced hours includes a 6.4 per cent increase in the
hourly pay rate and a cut in hours from 39 to 38. The first hour of overtime
will not now be paid at a higher rate. The deal means an overall pay
increase of just under 5 per cent, according to Incomes Data Services, the
pay research group.
</TEXT>
