<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 92 / Moynihan approves imports of gas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN opened its borders to gas trade with the rest of Europe yesterday by
approving two import deals and announcing the study of a pipeline link to
the Continent.
Mr Colin Moynihan, junior energy minister, told the Commons: 'A market in
which gas moves freely across frontiers and competes its way freely to final
consumers provides the best assurance for all . . . of the continued
development which will bring the environmental attractions of gas within
reach of the widest public.'
Mr Moynihan sanctioned an import deal agreed between National Power and
Statoil, Norway's state-owned oil and gas company, to buy 2.2bn cu metres of
gas a year.
Separately, he said Statoil could import a supply of gas to provide power
for one independent electricity generation project.
The approval leaves Statoil free to contribute the gas - about 1bn cu metres
of gas a year - to its agreed joint venture with BP and Norsk Hydro. The
three companies plan to set up a company in the UK to sell gas to the
industrial market.
The financial details of the deal will be finalised in the next month but it
is expected to involve Statoil and NH paying Pounds 10m to BP for a half
share in BP's existing gas marketing business in the UK.
Norwegian imports will go some way towards easing supply constraints in the
UK market, particularly in gas for power generation. A gas shortfall forced
up prices last year, making many proposed power stations uneconomic.
Although the Department of Energy has reversed its position on gas imports
since it vetoed British Gas's attempt to import Norwegian gas in 1985, Mr
Moynihan said yesterday that the department would still require importers to
submit individual deals for approval.
The feasibility of building a gas interconnector pipeline between the UK and
the Continent will be examined by six companies. Such a project is likely to
cost between Pounds 200m and Pounds 300m.
British Gas, British Petroleum, Conoco, Elf, Norsk Hydro and Statoil will
complete a study late this year. The group will be chaired by Mr Geoffrey
Chipperfield, chief executive of the Property Services Agency and former
permanent secretary to the Department of Energy.
The link is unlikely to be built unless the companies perceive demand for UK
gas in Europe at attractive prices.
Kinetica, one of the new independent gas companies, yesterday agreed a deal
with National Power to transport gas to a new power station on Humberside.
The company won the transit contract in competition with British Gas. It
will provide a pipeline link between a Conoco gas terminal at Theddlethorpe
in Lincolnshire and National Power's plant at Killingholme, Humberside.
</TEXT>
