<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 92 / Policy on supplies attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MISMANAGEMENT of Britain's natural gas supplies had necessitated the
decision to authorise imports from Norway, Mr Frank Dobson, the shadow
energy secretary, said in the Commons yesterday.
'Where there was abundance, the government's policies have created
shortage,' he said.
Mr Dobson protested that the government had encouraged the 'dash for gas' by
giving in to selfish demands of the privatised electricity companies instead
of telling them to consider Britain's long-term interests.
He feared that the UK would become dependent on gas imports not just from
Norway, but also from the Gulf, countries in the former Soviet Union and
from Algeria.
Mr Colin Moynihan, junior energy minister, told the Commons that it would be
necessary to examine the treaty with Norway concerning the Frigg field to
determine whether it required amending or renegotiating. He maintained that
the developments set in train would help significantly to open up
competition in the gas industry.
Mr Moynihan said companies participating in the feasibility study of a gas
pipeline between the UK and the Continent would be in a position to win
long-term contracts when the project was completed.
