<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 92 / SIB may drop unit trust plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Securities and In-vestments Board is preparing to drop its controversial
proposal to allow unit trusts to be sold through far more outlets than
competing life assurance products, according to industry sources.
SIB made the proposal, known as 'depolarisation', because it viewed unit
trust charges as more transparent to the prospective purchaser than those of
life assurance investments.
The proposal provoked an outcry from the life assurance industry, which saw
it as aiding its competitors.
Under polarisation, imposed with the Financial Services Act in 1987, sales
agents may be 'tied', selling the products of a single producer, or
'independent', selling the products of several producers. The rule was
intended to help consumers to gauge the objectivity of the advice they were
given.
Since 1987 the life assurance industry has adapted to polarisation, building
large sales networks around both types of distributors. The number of
outlets for unit trust companies has shrunk.
SIB is not expected to make a formal decision until its meeting next month,
but industry sources said recent informal soundings suggested the proposal
had already been dropped.
Among the reasons for the move is the opposition of consumer groups.
Ms Jean Eaglesham, money policy adviser for the Consumers' Association, said
her group opposed the move, partly because research showed that sales agents
frequently misled buyers about the company for which they were working.
Depolarisation would only make it easier for that confusion to occur, unless
sales agents were forced to disclose their employer much more clearly.
The Unit Trust Association, which supported the proposal, has found itself
deserted by five of its most powerful members - life assurance companies
which also sell unit trusts.
The association sent a paper to SIB supporting the proposal. It attacked the
sales methods of the life industry in support of its arguments. The
association has been forced to back down and is submitting a new paper to
SIB.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 5
</PAGE>
