FT  31 JAN 92 / Shamir insists loan funds will not be used in occupied
territories
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRIME MINISTER Yitzhak Shamir of Israel said yesterday none of the funds
Israel hopes to receive from US-guaranteed loans would be used for Jewish
settlements in the occupied territories, Reuter reports from Jerusalem.
'The funds we shall obtain through the loans will be devoted only, and
entirely, to the purpose of absorbing the olim (immigrants) and not for
building settlements,' he said.
Mr Shamir said he thought his declaration would satisfy Washington, which is
linking approval of Israel's request that it guarantee Dollars 10bn (Pounds
5.7bn) in loans to some form of a freeze in settlement in the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
'We will speak to (Washington), and we will see if it satisfies them,' Mr
Shamir said after a speech to an Israel Bond corporation conference.
Israel's ambassador to the US, Mr Zalman Shoval, said on returning from
Washington yesterday that there would be tough bargaining over US-imposed
settlement limits.
Mr Shoval said: 'We are only at the beginning of a very long process of
negotiations, and I definitely expect there will be difficulties. However, I
do hope a way will be found for us to get the guarantees.'
This week there were claims that Israel and Washington had reached a
compromise that no new settlements would be built after Israel completes
9,000 already started in the disputed territories. But Israeli officials
said the announcement was premature.
Mr Shamir called the reports 'incomplete and inexact,' and said the US had
shown 'a certain willingness' to compromise in Israel's favour.
In another development, leaders of the opposition Labour party yesterday
endorsed an agreement with Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's Likud party
setting the stage for early general elections on June 23.
'We will recommend holding the election on June 23,' Labour's parliamentary
chairman Mr Haim Ramon said.
Mr Shamir proposed early elections after losing his majority in parliament
last week when the far-right Tehiya and Moledet parties quit the coalition
in protest at perceived concessions to Palestinians in US-brokered Middle
East peace talks.
The elections had been originally scheduled for November.
