<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 92 / Arrest warrant issued for Nissan UK chairman
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Inland Revenue has issued a warrant for the arrest of Mr Octav Botnar,
chairman and managing director of Nissan UK, the former importer/distributor
of Nissan vehicles in Britain.
Mr Botnar, 78, was named in Teesside magistrates' court, Middlesbrough,
yesterday in charges brought against Mr Tore Arne Thorsen, manager of
Scansiris AS, a Norwegian freight transport company, alleging a corporation
tax fraud in which the pre-tax profits of NUK had been understated by Pounds
100m.
Separately Mr Michael Hunt, NUK assistant managing director and a
substantial personal shareholder in NUK, and Mr Frank Shannon, a former NUK
finance director, appeared in Worthing magistrates' court yesterday also
charged with alleged corporation tax fraud.
Mr Hunt, who was also named along with Mr Botnar in the charges against Mr
Thorsen, was charged in Worthing with alleged corporation tax frauds in
which NUK pre-tax profits had been understated by a total of Pounds 150m
over a period of 17 years. Mr Hunt, 58, was charged on two counts.
The first alleged that he had 'cheated' the Inland Revenue of corporation
tax between December 1 1982 and December 31 1991 'with intent to defraud'.
The charge alleged that he had arranged 'dishonestly' for the preparation of
'falsely inflated' invoices by Scansiris showing sums for freight charges
allegedly due from Nissan UK.
The charge stated that the invoices were charged in the Nissan UK accounts
for the years ended July 31 1983 to July 31 1992, causing pre-tax profits to
be understated by about Pounds 100m.
In the Middlesbrough magistrates' court the same detailed charge was made
against Mr Thorsen that 'together with Octav Botnar and Michael Hunt' he had
cheated the Inland Revenue with 'intent to defraud'.
Mr Hunt was also charged along with Mr Shannon that they had 'cheated' the
Inland Revenue of corporation tax between October 1 1975 and March 31 1983
'with intent to defraud'.
The charges alleged that they had arranged 'dishonestly' for the preparation
of 'falsely inflated' invoices by a Dutch company Autocontex BV showing sums
for freight charges allegedly due from Datsun UK (now called Nissan UK).
The charges stated that the invoices were charged in the Nissan UK accounts
for the accounting periods ended December 31 1976 to July 31 1983 causing
pre-tax profits to be understated by around Pounds 50m.
Mr Hunt and Mr Shannon are to appear again in Worthing magistrates' court on
February 25. Mr Thorsen from Grimstad, Norway, is to appear again in
Teesside magistrates' court on March 26. All three were released on bail.
Mr Hunt was released on bail totalling Pounds 175,000 and on condition that
he surrendered his passport and resided at home.
He gave an undertaking 'not to exert influence concerning the investigation
of the prosecution on any witnesses or potential witnesses including persons
who have connections with Nissan UK past or present'.
Nissan UK said yesterday that Mr Botnar was on holiday in Switzerland.
The Inland Revenue said: 'What we do in these cases is to approach the
lawyers of the person and invite them to come back.'
The Inland Revenue mounted a dawn raid against Nissan UK in June last year.
Codenamed Operation Bluebird, it was the largest search undertaken by the
Inland Revenue involving 135 of its officers.
In all 13 locations were searched, including the Worthing headquarters of
Nissan UK, the offices of some of its legal and financial advisers and the
homes of some current and former directors.
Late last year Mr Shannon, Mr Brian Laventure, a partner in the Portsmouth
office of Grant Thornton, the personal and corporate tax adviser to Nissan
UK, and Mr Gerald Compton, a partner in Kidsons Impey, the NUK auditor, were
arrested and charged with conspiracy to cheat the Inland Revenue.
They were charged in Worthing magistrates' court with conspiring to cheat
the Inland Revenue by filing false stock relief claims for Datsun UK, the
former name of Nissan UK, for the accounting periods ended July 31 1980 and
the year ended July 31 1981 amounting to Pounds 9m and Pounds 5.5m.
The charges claimed specifically that the three men conspired between March
19 1980 and July 14 1984 at Worthing and elsewhere:
To bring forward the accounting date for Datsun UK from December 31 1980 to
July 31 1980, 'falsely representing' that the change had been done for
commercial reasons unconnected to any tax liability, whereas 'the sole or
main benefit' of the change had been to increase Datsun's claim to stock
relief, and
Had caused the Inland Revenue to allow Datsun UK false stock relief claims
for the two periods of around Pounds 9m and Pounds 5.5m respectively.
They are due to appear again in Worthing magistrates' court on these charges
in late February.
Nissan UK lost the Nissan franchise in Britain from the start of this year,
when Nissan Motor, Japan's second-largest carmaker, set up its own
operations following a protracted and bitter conflict between the two
companies.
Driver licence centre accused in Nissan row, Page 7
</TEXT>
