<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 92 / Companies acquitted over Blue Arrow rights issue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ALL three corporate defen-dants in the Blue Arrow fraud trial
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
County NatWest, NatWest Investment Bank and UBS Phillips &amp; Drew Securities -
were acquitted yesterday of joining the alleged conspiracy to mislead the
markets over the result of the employment agency's 1987 rights issue.
Instructing the Old Bailey jury to acquit the companies, the judge, Mr
Justice McKinnon, ruled that there was insufficient evidence for the cases
against them to proceed any further. With five of their former employees
still on trial, the companies issued only the briefest of statements
following the acquittals.
A National Westminster spokesman said that the parent bank was 'pleased'
that its subsidiary companies had been acquitted. UBS Phillips &amp; Drew
welcomed the judge's ruling but said no further comment could be made while
the trial against the individual defendants continued.
Mr Justice McKinnon said the companies' acquittals did not affect the cases
against the remaining five individual defendants in any way.
'There are legal and separate evidential reasons concerning the companies
and how they can be liable in respect of crime which have led me to my
direction,' he told the jury.
The five defendants now left in the trial are: Mr Jonathan Cohen, a former
County chief executive; Mr David Reed, a former head of corporate finance at
County; Mr Nicholas Wells, a former County corporate finance director; Mr
Martin Gibbs, a former head of corporate finance at P&amp;D; and Mr Christopher
Stainforth, a former P&amp;D director.
Each individual defendant had had the authority of his employer to buy the
shares taken by County and P&amp;D in the rights issue, the judge said.
'There is no suggestion that any one of the individual defendants was on a
frolic of his own,' he added.
The jury, which had not sat since mid-December, was recalled to return the
not guilty verdicts. The judge told the jury he had reached his decision to
acquit P&amp;D on December 19 last year and his decision regarding the two
NatWest subsidiaries on January 17.
Costs - estimated at several million pounds - were awarded in the companies'
favour.
The trial will resume on Tuesday when Mr Justice McKinnon will begin his
summing up.
He told the jury that in his summing up he would have particular things to
say about Mr Stainforth.
The trial, which started on February 11 last year, is one of the longest in
criminal history. With estimates of its total cost exceeding Pounds 35m, it
will be the most expensive.
Defendants shake off blues, Page 6
</TEXT>
