<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 92 / World Stock Markets (Europe): German carmakers come into the
limelight
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Markets Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CARMAKERS came more broadly into the limelight yesterday as the big German
groups replaced Volvo as the centre of international investment attention,
writes Our Markets Staff.
FRANKFURT majored on the motor industry as Volkswagen rose DM10 to DM338 and
BMW by DM6 to DM523.50, VW and Daimler heading the active stocks list in
turnover of DM888m, and DM864m.
German stock market turnover rose from DM6.4bn to DM6.6bn as blue chips led
equities higher. After a 1.59 fall to 679.34 in the broadly-based FAZ index
at midsession, the 30-share DAX closed 8.51 higher at 1,680.91.
Mr Bob Barber, who heads the European automotive and capital goods analysis
team at James Capel, was not impressed with VW, noting that the company,
which underperformed the market last year, faced an estimated drop of 12 per
cent in new German car sales this year with 40 per cent of its own sales
going into the domestic market.
BMW yesterday confirmed that its sales and profits were higher in 1991, and
forecast higher production and sales figures for the current year.
In electricals, AEG had another of its sporadic surges, rising DM9.80 to
DM224.20 and the battery group, Varta, rose DM11.50 to DM302. It said
yesterday that final talks on a cooperation accord had begun with Japan's
Toshiba Battery, and Duracell of the US on the production of rechargeable
nickel hydride batteries.
PARIS came back from its highs after an active day's trading. The CAC-40
index slipped 5.70 to 1,873.94 in relatively heavy volume of FFr3.2bn.
Synthelabo, the pharmaceutical company controlled by L'Oreal, was unusually
active as 92,700 shares or around 1 per cent of the company were put through
the market in several large blocks. The stock fell FFr6 to FFr1,095. A
spokesman for Goldman Sachs would only say that it had placed less than 5
per cent of the company yesterday.
Dealers believed that the shares had come from the owners of companies
recently taken over by Synthelabo and had been placed with institutions.
Pernod Ricard, the drinks group, rose to an all-time high of FFr1,534 on
continued takeover speculation before closing FFr10 down at FFr1,485 with a
heavy 149,000 shares traded.
Paribas ended FFr7.50 lower at FFr347.50 with 217,866 shares traded. After
the close the bank announced that it had made a net attributable loss of
FFr200m in 1991, which came in below expectations which had already been
downgraded after the recent disclosure of heavy provisions for loans to
Maxwell companies.
MILAN weakened during the official session following the overnight loss on
Wall Street. The Comit index fell 7.26 to 537.81 in turnover estimated at
L100bn after Wednesday's L105.8bn.
Fiat fell L133 or 2.6 per cent to L5,028 in the wake of its poor 1991
results and slipped to L5,025 after hours.
The telecommunications sector came under pressure on rumours that Stet was
launching a big bond with warrants into Sip savings shares and there were
fears of heavy earnings dilution as a result. Stet slipped L13 to L2,261
while Sip savings shares fell L55 or 4 per cent to L1,320.
STOCKHOLM saw another fall in Volvo in the aftermath of the abortive
Volvo/Procordia merger. The B shares fell SKr7 to SKr378 on the day and 10
per cent from Monday's intraday peak of SKr420.
The Affarsvarlden General index dropped 6.2 to 967.5 as brokers said that
the market was also beginning to be troubled by the prospect of the Swedish
corporate results seasons which begins next week. Market rumours indicate
disappointing results from Electrolux, due to produce preliminary figures on
next Tuesday. Yesterday the B shares slipped SKr3 to SKr239.
AMSTERDAM slipped back slightly, the CBS Tendency Index shedding 0.1 to
121.00 in turnover of Fl 539.8m.
Elsevier, which announced a strong profit forecast, rose Fl 2.40 to Fl
105.40. UK interest was reported to be heavy. Elsewhere in the publishing
sector VNU rose Fl 0.5 to Fl 83.00.
MADRID's general index fell 0.07 to 253.80. Asland, the cement group, which
played down reports of possible US court action, drifted Pta40 to Pta2,065.
Volume in Iberdrola, the utility, was high at 2.7m shares: the share price
picked up Pta2 to Pta723. Telefonica continued its fall on the back of the
pension fund problems, losing Pta5 to Pta1,160.
OSLO gained in dull trading, the all-share index moving 1.5 to 445.00 in
turnover of NKr217m. Saga B rose NKr4.5 to NKr95.5 on reports that the UK
may lift a ban on imports of Norwegian gas.
