<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MARSH &amp; MCLENNAN, the world's biggest insurance broker, yesterday turned in
stagnant fourth-quarter and full-year earnings, writes Karen Zagor.
For the three months to December 31, the company had net income of Dollars
54.2m, compared with Dollars 54.5m a year earlier. However, fewer
outstanding shares helped earnings per share rise to 75 cents in the 1991
quarter from 74 cents the previous year.
The 1991 figures include extraordinary pre-tax gains of Dollars 10m.
Revenues were only slightly lower, at Dollars 665.9m against Dollars 668.5m
in the 1990 quarter.
For the whole of 1991, net earnings were Dollars 305.5m, or Dollars 4.18 a
share, on revenues of Dollars 2.78bn, compared with earnings of Dollars
304.1m, or Dollars 4.15, on revenues of Dollars 2.72bn.
