<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 92 / International Company News: Paribas pushed into the red by
Maxwell provisions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE collapse of the Maxwell empire contributed to FFr2.8bn (Dollars 510m) of
extraordinary provisions made last year by Paribas, the French investment
banking group, and to its slide into an estimated net loss of FFr200m for
1991 from net profits of FFr2.5bn in 1990.
Moody's, the US credit rating agency, yesterday announced it was putting
Paribas' loans and long-term debt under surveillance for a possible rating
reduction. Moody's will pay particular attention to the possible
deterioration in the quality of the banking group's assets.
Paribas, like several other prominent Parisian banks including Credit
Lyonnais and Banque Nationale de Paris (BNP), made a number of loans to the
Maxwell companies through its Paribas Suisse subsidiary. It has fully
covered its exposure to Maxwell interests with an extraordinary provision of
FFr800m.
Credit Lyonnais and BNP, both state-owned banks, have far higher exposure to
the Maxwell debacle than Paribas. Paris banking analysts estimate that the
overall level of Maxwell loans owed to the French banking industry is around
FFr15bn.
The announcement of Paribas' provisions came as no surprise to the French
stock market given that Mr Andre Levy Lang, president, had warned that his
group would be making provisions on a number of large corporate loans.
Paribas later issued a statement saying it would also be making provisions
for its Maxwell loans.
Despite the high level of loan loss provisions and the competitive state of
the international banking industry, Paribas managed to increase its
operating income to FFr3bn from FFr1.6bn including minority interests in
1991, and to FFr1.7bn from FFr400m excluding minorities.
However, the group experienced a fall in income from capital transactions to
FFr800m from FFr2.5bn including minorities, and to FFr700m from FFr2.1bn
excluding minorities. Paribas said this reflected the state of the market.
The level of ordinary banking provisions rose to FFr6.6bn from FFr5.5bn in
1991. Net profits including minority interests fell to FFr1bn from FFr4.1bn.
</TEXT>
