<DOCNO>FT921-11522</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CA4AUABXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920131
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 92 / The Lex Column: UK brewing
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK beer market's capacity for change is becoming slightly unnerving. The
deals announced yesterday between Bass and two local London brewers
illustrate the latest trend - the revival of real ale and the retreat of
lager. Bass is to sell old-style bitter from Young's and Fuller's in its
pubs while they sell Bass lager in exchange. From Bass's viewpoint, this may
be a pragmatic response to a shift in fashion. The wider question is how far
the economics of big brewing rely on lager holding its 50-plus per cent
share of the national market.
Given the distorting effects of recession, the underlying pattern is not yet
clear. But while premium lagers may not be losing ground, the big standard
lagers and keg bitters are. These are the brands which offer the national
brewer the biggest economies of scale and provide barriers to entry. Some
ground may therefore be lost to competition. The big brewers will still
control the channels of distribution; whether they can command the same
margins in a fragmented market is another matter.
It might be thought that the regional brewers would benefit accordingly. But
control of distribution is everything. In 1988, Marston's, another regional
brewer, did a pioneering bitter-for-lager deal with Whitbread. Within three
years, Marston's said, sales of its main brand should be up 50 per cent.
Three years on, its profits are lower than they were then. Sales through
Whitbread, it says, 'continue to be disappointing'. It seems the diversity
which is the consumer's gain is also the industry's loss.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 20
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-11523</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CA4AUABWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920131
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 92 / The Lex Column: Rank Organisation
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Investors were deceived by Lonrho's example in marking Rank down so steeply
this week. There was no dividend cut after all; earnings are more than
enough to cover a maintained payment. There was no rights issue either;
gearing is high but there is no immediate pressure to reduce it. Yesterday's
8 per cent jump in the share price leaves it slightly higher than before the
scare. But there is still the question of whether the underperformance of
nearly 40 per cent since mid-1989 is now set to reverse.
Even without much help from the economy, Rank should manage a modest
increase in profit this year, while funding enough capital spending from
cash flow to maintain an edge over its competition. Disposals will reduce
gearing, though probably not to the long-term target range of 50 per cent.
That does not point to a higher dividend, but it should at least be
maintained. The yield is thus 6 1/2 per cent, a comfortable underpinning for
a recovery stock.
Any revival of consumer confidence should feed through quickly into margins.
In Rank's case the earnings benefit would be compounded by a reduction in
the tax rate, as a smaller proportion of group profits would flow from
highly-taxed Rank Xerox. The ACT problem which cost Pounds 7m should also
disappear. A prospective multiple of 13 thus looks undemanding, especially
since fears of a Mecca black hole are dying down.
</TEXT>
