<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 92 / The Lex Column: Sir Bryan's soft farewell
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
FT-SE Index: 2,550.8 (+4.3)
It is tempting to wonder how Sir James McKinnon would have approached
yesterday's consultative paper from Oftel on BT's prices. Instead of the
thorough but uncontroversial document produced by the retiring Sir Bryan
Carsberg, the gas regulator might have thrown a brickbat or two on behalf of
consumers. As the market was quick to realise, the absence in Oftel's paper
of any severe response to BT's continued market dominance augurs well for
shareholders, less so for customers. It looks as if Sir Bryan intends to go
quietly.
Indeed, the striking thing about BT's sluggish third quarter results was the
neatness of their fit with Oftel's views on BT's proper rate of return.
Recession and the tighter price cap introduced by last year's duopoly review
have temporarily reduced BT's return on capital to just below 20 per cent.
But that is still near the upper end of the range regarded as acceptable by
the regulator. If BT can do this well in a recession, it can presumably earn
excessive returns later on. Whether it does so will be the measure of
Oftel's success in this pricing review.
It has emerged that while BT makes losses on line rentals and profits from
UK long distance calls, they are respectively much smaller and larger than
was generally suspected. As Oftel says, BT's case for a swift rebalancing of
prices to remove this cross-subsidy looks correspondingly weaker. Doubtless,
Mercury will be pleased; competing with BT's call charges is clearly not as
difficult as it should be. It should also please domestic customers, who
would bear the brunt of higher rentals.
</TEXT>
