<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 92 / Lloyd's counters forecast of losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE dispute between Lloyd's of London and Chatset, the independent analysis
company, over the insurance market's 1990 and 1991 results deepened
yesterday.
On Wednesday Chatset published its own forecast and estimated that Lloyd's
faces losses of Pounds 1bn for its 1990 underwriting year and Pounds 750m
for last year. Lloyd's will report the results in June next year and the
year after.
A number of underwriters disputed the projections and yesterday Lloyd's
issued its own estimates.
They are derived from individual forecasts given by a market group of
managing agents representing about 40 per cent of the market.
Lloyd's claim that the market will register a loss of Pounds 390.5m for 1990
and a profit of Pounds 424.5m for last year.
The figures exclude investment income, expenses and the reinsurance to close
that individual underwriters will decide when closing their accounts.
They also exclude the impact of further claims emerging from business
underwritten before 1990. Chatset estimates that such claims might cost at
least Pounds 400m a year, although the figure is disputed by Lloyd's.
Mr David Coleridge, Lloyd's chairman, described Chatset's figures as
'unnecessarily pessimistic and alarmist'.
The House of Lords yesterday gave Lloyd's leave to appeal on a preliminary
issue in the legal case being brought against the corporation by 33 Names
who were members of insurance syndicates managed by the Oakeley Vaughan
managing agency, now in liquidation.
The Names - the individuals who pledge their wealth to back the market  -
say their losses were due to the failure of the Lloyd's Corporation, which
provides market back-up and regulatory services, to regulate the market
properly.
Lloyd's wants the issue of whether it owes Names a legal duty of care to be
heard on technical grounds outside the facts of the case.
It appealed to the lords after losing on the same issue in the appeal court
last September.
</TEXT>
