FT  31 JAN 92 / Midland to cut 300 jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MIDLAND BANK is to cut 300 more jobs from its 27,000-strong UK workforce,
David Barchard writes.
The bank said yesterday that the cuts were being made throughout its
operation, but applied mainly to back-office staff. A number of managerial
posts will be among those to go. Midland hopes to keep redundancies to a
minimum by not replacing staff as they retire and by transferring staff
whose jobs are to be cut to new positions.
Last year the bank shed 4,000 jobs to cut its costs, which are among the
highest in the UK banking industry. Midland made a loss of Pounds 71m in the
first half of 1991 and is due to announce its full-year results next month.
Banks have been making large cuts in their workforces for several years
because of of the introduction of new technology.
