<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): Steep fall in size of wage deals
likely to continue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE 'dramatic' fall in pay deals last year continued into the final quarter
and looks likely to persist this year, possibly even breaching the 5 per
cent 'pay floor', according to pay research body Industrial Relations
Services.
The latest figures from the IRS pay databank for the final quarter of last
year, based on pay reviews for 630,000 employees, show that the median
settlement has fallen to 5.1 per cent. The figure for December 1990 was 9.7
per cent.
IRS says that nine out of 10 pay reviews in the final three months of last
year were for smaller amounts than awarded in the same period the year
before.
December's lower quartile of settlements remains unchanged from November at
4.5 per cent, while the upper quartile has increased slightly to 6.7 per
cent.
IRS says that a striking feature of pay in the 1980s was the existence of a
'pay floor' of 5 per cent, in spite of persistently low inflation during
1986 and 1987.
Public-sector pay in the financial year to March next year is expected to
increase by 7 per cent, according to a separate analysis by the Public
Finance Foundation. The PFF estimates that public-sector rises will be 1
percentage point higher than private-sector pay and 3.5 percentage points
higher than inflation.
The PFF expects that next week the pay review bodies will announce rises of
about 6 per cent for the 1.5m teachers, doctors, nurses and members of the
armed forces.
It also predicts that local-government settlements in July and September
will be 4.5 per cent and the Civil Service settlement will be 5 per cent.
</TEXT>
