<TEXT>
ORDERS for west German plant and machinery rose last month for the first
time in a year, the VDMA manufacturers' association said yesterday. Export
demand was 3 per cent higher and German orders were 4 per cent up in real
terms on December 1990, writes Christopher Parkes in Bonn.
The aggregate 4 per cent rise was one bright spot in a year in which the
value of orders fell 8 per cent. However, the VDMA said it was too soon to
say if the decline, especially in overseas markets, had stopped. Foreign
demand for the year was 17 per cent down in real terms.
