<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JAN 92 / International Company News: CCE in Dollars 1.5bn corporate
bond offering
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
COCA-COLA Enterprises (CCE), the leading US bottler of Coca-Cola which is 44
per cent owned by the parent company, yesterday sold Dollars 1.5bn of bonds,
one of the largest US corporate bond issues of the past 12 months, writes
Alan Friedman in New York.
Salomon Brothers, the sole manager of the bond offer, said Dollars 550m of
the proceeds will be used in a tender offer to buy back senior and
subordinated notes issued by Johnston Coca-Cola Bottling, a unit of CCE. The
remaining Dollars 950m will be used to redeem other CCE debt.
The CCE offer, priced yesterday, was supposed to consist of Dollars 1bn of
10 and 30-year notes. Strong demand resulted in the issue being expanded to
include Dollars 500m of 10-year notes, Dollars 250m of 20-year paper and
Dollars 750m of 30-year bonds.
The 10-year paper, with a 7.875 per cent coupon, was priced at par, as was
the 20-year issue, with a coupon of 8.50 per cent. The 30-year bonds, was
priced at 98.83 to yield 8.61 per cent.
These pricings represent, respectively, spreads of 68, 78 and 89 basis
points above US Treasury bonds of comparable maturities.
