<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JAN 92 / UK Company News: Administrators rule out any early disposal
of controlling stake in MGN
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN EARLY sale of a con-trolling interest in Mirror Group Newspapers was last
night ruled out by the administrators of Mr Robert Maxwell's private
interests.
In an apparent attempt to end speculation, Mr John Talbot, one of the
administrators, said last night that the late Mr Maxwell's controlling 51
per cent stake was not for sale at present. The stake is effectively owned
by banks such as Midland and National Westminster because they were pledged
as collateral to cover Maxwell debt.
The administrators said they have received a considerable number of
approaches for the MGN stake from groups not yet publicly identified.
Last night's statement said that the administrators were co-operating with
the board of MGN 'and will give consideration to the timing of any sale of
the shares, if appropriate, when comprehensive information is available from
the board.'
This implies that no decision is likely for a matter of months. Audited
accounts for 1991 are not likely to be available before April.
'The administrators are working closely with banks who have taken security
over MGN shares and who have indicated they support the course of action
being taken by the administrators,' the statement added.
The announcement came as a disappointment to Sir Peter Parker, chairman of a
management buy-out group at MGN which includes Mr Richard Stott, editor of
the Daily Mirror.
The group was pressing for an early sale on the grounds that delay and
uncertainty would damage MGN.
Last night the group said: 'It is not clear who this delay benefits but we
have not withdrawn our interest.'
Hambros Bank has also said it is interested in putting together a consortium
to bid for MGN.
</TEXT>
