<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JAN 92 / The Lex Column: UK construction
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
An election has to be in the offing when a government minister needs to
exclude commercial property and make five-monthly comparisons to derive any
satisfaction from the latest construction figures. That said, there is
plausible evidence of a modest pick-up in construction orders from the
private industrial sector between July and November last year. That is
certainly consistent with the idea that companies will not wish to be left
with outdated plant and equipment when a strong recovery finally
materialises.
Unfortunately, these tidings bring little comfort for investors in quoted
contractors. As the Building Employers Confederation made clear over the
weekend, many of its members are undertaking work on zero or negative
margins as they compete fiercely for the dwindling volume of new commercial
work. Returns on the civil side are more encouraging for the moment, but
this will not necessarily last if everyone dives into the same market place.
Any increase in orders is not to be sniffed at. But just as increased demand
in the mortgage market will be slow to feed through into bigger profits for
the housebuilders, so the contractors will have to wait awhile for better
margins.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
