<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JAN 92 / Russia issues economic union ultimatum
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RUSSIA yesterday issued an ultimatum to other former Soviet republics either
to join a trade, banking and currency union or face a dangerous regime of
trade restrictions and higher prices.
Mr Vladimir Mashits, the newly appointed minister for relations with other
republics, said Russia had already agreed with Kazakhstan and Belarus to set
up a single economic space and rouble zone. Kirghizia would be next on the
list.
'With whom else will we sign such an agreement? . . . We'll see,' he said.
'We are ready to have one close group of friends and another not so close.'
He said a preferential regime would be open to republics which:
Dropped plans to issue their own currencies or surrogate money; Agreed on a
system of consultation among their central banks;
Resisted re-exporting cheap Russian energy for hard currency.
The veiled threat of economic warfare if they did not comply reflects, in
part, Russia's desperate need for a clearly defined currency and banking
zone to strengthen the rouble.
Mr Mashits used the tense relationship with Ukraine to illustrate the
dangers of a trade war. He said if Ukraine insisted on charging a new high
price for its coal of Rbs1,600 per tonne (as opposed to Rbs200), 'you can
imagine what our retaliatory price will be for oil'.
Alternatively, Russia could withhold sales of oil to Ukraine, but 'that
would ruin her economy and we will stop getting metal, coal and chemical
products'.
He said his new ministry would deal with a host of practical problems
resulting from the union's collapse. These included dividing up Baltic Sea
fishing waters, formerly open to all former Soviet citizens.
The tough stance also appeared to be aimed at public opinion, which not only
bitterly resents the government's harsh economic reforms, but complains that
Russia is subsidising other republics with cheap oil while their neighbours
plot to wreck the rouble with separate currencies.
The combative announcement followed claims by Lithuania on Tuesday that
Russia had cut off oil supplies. Although he partially denied the claim, Mr
Mashits said that Lithuanians had enough oil, accused them of demanding hard
currency for deliveries of fertiliser to Russia and attacked their attempts
to take over Soviet army property while demanding the evacuation of homeless
troops.
Ukraine rejects joint line on foreign debt, Page 2
</TEXT>
