<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JAN 92 / Traffic wardens brought to book
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE POPULAR image of traffic wardens as a ruthlessly efficient machine for
persecuting motorists takes an unprecedented bashing today, writes Richard
Tomkins.
As neglected by their employers as they are unloved by the public, traffic
wardens emerge as a badly managed crew which spends less than half its
average working day sticking tickets to motorists' windscreens.
A highly critical report by the Audit Commission portrays them not as petty
Hitlers, but as the Cinderellas of law enforcement, neglected by the police
forces and local authorities which employ them.
In what amounts to a 24-page ticket of violations against management of
parking enforcement, the commission paints a dismal picture of indifference.
Objectives are 'vague and unquantified' and day-to-day management is often
'languid'.
Many motorists might view the identified management failings as a blessing
in disguise.
The commission says, for example, that traffic wardens spend up to 45 per
cent of their working day walking to and from their beat. With morning
parades and tea breaks added in, less than half the working day is spent
productively.
Among the report's other indictments of the service are:
Supervision of wardens on the streets is minimal or absent, and no analysis
is undertaken to check how they spend their hours on duty.
Sickness levels average 30 days a year - double the level of police officers
in the same forces and four times the UK average for manual workers.
Working hours are inflexible. In one town centre where waiting restrictions
apply until 6.30pm, all wardens leave the streets at 4.30pm, just as the
evening rush hour starts. The number of tickets issued daily by wardens
varies. It is four times as high in some forces as it is in others.
The proportion of unpaid tickets written off by police forces outside London
varies from 3 per cent to 13 per cent.
In the 30 years since the creation of the traffic warden service, the police
have failed to devise an appropriate measure of performance.
Traffic warden numbers tend to be based on historic decisions, not justified
by the economies of substituting wardens for police officers.
The report concludes that a well-managed and efficient service would save
money and reduce inconvenience.
'If it is worth the police service spending Pounds 50m a year on traffic
wardens, it is worth managing them well,' it says. 'If the subject is not
worth this expenditure, then it is worth reviewing it to identify the scope
for savings.'
Fine Lines: Improving the Traffic Warden Service. The Audit Commission.
HMSO. Pounds 6.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
