<TEXT>
It is hard to believe there is such a thing as a Finnish double of News
Corporation's Rupert Murdoch, but it looks as though the digger has just
recruited one to his board.
The 59-year-old Aatos Erkko, chief executive of The Sanoma Group for the
past 20 years, is nowhere near as well known as Hamish Maxwell, the former
chief executive of Philip Morris who has also joined. But our man in
Helsinki reports that he is a very big wheel. He owns Finland's biggest
selling daily, Helsingin Sanomat, and has extensive interests in magazines
and cable TV.
In the past his family has provided several politicians, but the
publicity-shy Erkko does not interfere editorially in his papers. He also
differs from Murdoch in that he does not need to borrow from banks and has
no heirs. Part of the attraction, perhaps?
