FT  30 JAN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Labour fears over election
resources - Party finances
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE HECTIC pace of recent campaigning has aroused fears that Labour has been
forced to dip into funds set aside for the general election, raising fresh
questions about its capacity to finance up to five more months of flat-out
electioneering.
The party's concerted attempts to regain the political initiative have meant
it has overshot projected spending levels, according to one senior party
official.
Although the statement was dismissed as 'not true' by Mr Jack Cunningham,
Labour's campaign co-ordinator, other senior party figures admitted that
hard decisions would soon have to be made.
Labour said last month its campaign war-chest exceeded its Pounds 6m target,
but this is likely to be dwarfed by a Tory fighting fund estimated at Pounds
20m.
In 1990 - the latest figures available - Labour withdrew Pounds 570,000 from
its general election fund, using the money mainly to employ 'temporary'
organisers 'covering areas of the country crucial to our success at the next
general election'. This did not prevent the fund more than doubling in size
to Pounds 2.6m from Pounds 1.26m a year earlier.
However, the party's general fund clocked up a 1990 loss of Pounds 289,000
against a projected break-even.
