<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JAN 92 / Political Notebook: The rail cost of privatisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There is only one manifesto commitment the Conservatives could make that
might be as damaging as their 1987 poll tax pledge. That would be a promise
to inject voters with bubonic plague.
That view, offered only half-jokingly by one of the leading players in Mr
John Major's cabinet, is understandable enough. Ideology was the driving
force behind the poll tax. The party now is led by a careful man who puts
common sense before abstract credo. His manifesto will preach caring
Conservatism, not permanent revolution. The logic seems impeccable. The
conclusion could prove misplaced.
The debate over how the Conservatives should privatise the railways -
assuming of course they win the election - has obscured a more basic
political reality. As a handful of Whitehall insiders are beginning to
realise, the break-up of British Rail has the volcanic potential to make the
poll tax look like a small tremor.
The government will fight the election committed to privatisation. Mr
Malcolm Rifkind plans to publish a white paper sometime before then. The
transport secretary had hoped to produce it in December. He presented the
prime minister with what seemed then to be a plausible blueprint.
Briefly, the network would be opened to competition; InterCity and the
freight operations would be sold; the loss-making Network SouthEast and the
other regional services would remain in state ownership but their operations
would be franchised out to private companies.
That model did not win instant approval in Downing Street. On one level, Mr
Major's policy unit thought not enough detailed work had been done. How
would the new system be regulated to ensure that operators ran essential
services, how would subsidies be fixed, who would own the stations?
On another level, Mr Major preferred the more romantic notion that the
pre-1948 regional companies could be re-created.
To complicate things, Mr Peter Lilley wanted much greater competition,
throwing the Department of Trade and Industry's weight behind the idea of a
separate rail-track authority on which operators would compete for business.
The latest talk is of a hybrid solution: InterCity might be sold off intact,
with regional companies revived and given permission to use its tracks.
But some ministers have begun to stand back from the argument over detail to
take a broader view of the political risks. They do not like what they see.
Westminster gossip has it that Mr Chris Patten is among those arguing that
the white paper should confine itself to general principles.
British Rail is unlike any previous privatisation. It is a monopoly in which
the customer travels on the production line. It loses vast amounts of money.
It has no real prospect of making any. Even those parts - such as InterCity
 -which are notionally profitable on paper would not survive real accounting
criteria.
Theoretically the network could be made profitable if fares for commuters in
the south-east were raised by 50 per cent or so, the regional networks
slashed, and the loss-making 'ends' chopped from the InterCity network.
Those are hardly options, unless Mr Major wants to be certain of losing the
election after next.
Fares will go up. That is the most obvious lesson of all privatisations. But
unless still more passengers are to be driven on to clogged roads or the
government is ready to raise sharply the cost of motoring, the network will
not survive without large state subsidies. The private-sector ethos and
semblance of competition provided by franchising will not be a sufficient
substitute for the taxpayers' money needed to make up for decades of
under-investment.
Nor is franchising as simple as it sounds. A glance at the mess made of the
auctioning of commercial television licences provides ample evidence of the
capacity for mistakes. It hardly matters if there is nothing new on TV-am
for 12 months or so. Commuters from Tunbridge Wells would feel rather more
aggrieved if a rail franchise operator decided to take a few trains from its
schedule if its contract were not renewed.
Such problems could be solved with enough money. But enthusiasts for
privatisation have not paid enough attention to the Treasury agenda.
Whitehall's most powerful department has a simple objective - to stop
spending money on the railways. It usually gets its way.
The Treasury's refusal to spend more money ensured the poll tax was
destroyed before it started. Mr Major might reflect that voters felt the
impact of that mistake once a year. If rail privatisation went wrong,
millions would be reminded of his error twice a day.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 11 Illustration (Omitted).
