<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JAN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Parties clash on taxation and
benefits - Election campaigning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TWO biggest parties yesterday struggled to hold the media spotlight with
Labour switching its campaign to pensions and benefits and the Tories
concentrating their fire on the opposition's tax and spending plans.
At rival briefings in Westminster, Labour fielded Mr John Smith, the shadow
chancellor, to challenge the government's record on child benefits and
pensions while officials at Tory Central Office issued a new dossier
entitled Labour's Tax Shambles.
Mr Smith used his platform to contrast his commitments to increased benefits
with the claim that the government's efforts to hold down child benefit had
cost a family with two children Pounds 404 since 1987.
Touching on this week's row over value added tax, he claimed that 1988
figures showed indirect taxation meant the poorest fifth of pensioner
households paid nearly 40 per cent of their gross income in tax while the
richest fifth of non-retired households paid just 34 per cent of their
income in tax.
Commending Labour's commitment to increase pensions by Pounds 5 for single
people and Pounds 8 for couples and to increase child benefit to Pounds 9.95
a week, he said the differences in the tax burden were a direct consequence
of 'bizarre and deeply unfair' Tory policies.
He was backed by Ms Harriet Harman, shadow health minister, who claimed that
government neglect had meant one in four British children lived at poverty
levels - double the figure that the government had inherited in 1979.
Mr Chris Patten, the Conservative party chairman, presented an eight-page
assault on Labour's past statements on tax and spending.
Claiming that Labour's charge that the government would lift VAT from 17.5
per cent to 22 per cent was a 'scare' story intended to distract the voters'
from its own confusion on tax, he argued that 'the shambles' over the past
few weeks had destroyed Labour's credibility.
His attack was echoed by Mr Tony Newton, the social security secretary, who
claimed his Labour shadow, Mr Michael Meacher, had committed his party to
Pounds 15bn of unfunded expenditure on benefits.
On National Insurance, Mr Smith would not say whether the removal of the
ceiling on contributions would be immediate or phased. The decision could be
taken only after the Budget or when Labour saw undisclosed Treasury figures
after a general election.
He went on to reject Tory claims that repayment of NI contribution
overpayments to those earning below Pounds 21,000 would be costly or
complicated.
</TEXT>
