<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JAN 92 / MPs told of watchdog's pay-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FORMER chief executive of the National Rivers Authority agreed a Pounds
125,000 compensation deal with the authority's board after resigning last
year, a committee of MPs heard yesterday.
Mr John Bowman left the water watchdog in June following serious financial
weakness for which all board members were ultimately responsible, the MPs
were told.
The board decided Mr Bowman should leave after an internal inquiry
discovered lax management controls had led to overspending of at least
Pounds 1m of taxpayers' money on a new headquarters building. Two senior
managers were disciplined.
However, a memorandum by the National Audit Office, the public spending
watchdog, shows that the Department of Environment had told the NRA that
principle responsibility for effective financial management lay with the
authority's board as well as the chief executive.
It reveals that, as well as informing Mr Bowman of his responsibilities, a
letter about the line of responsibility had been sent to Lord Crickhowell,
the NRA chairman.
Mr John Wheatley, the new NRA chief executive, told the Commons' public
accounts committee that the board decided Mr Bowman should leave the NRA on
'agreed terms'. The Pounds 125,000 was in compensation for the unexpired
part of his five-year contract.
Mr Wheatley, a board member at the time, said there had been 'no
justification' for dismissing Mr Bowman. Asked if the board had agreed to
pay compensation in order to conceal its own shortcomings, he replied: 'That
was not in our mind.'
The NRA, which monitors the state of the water environment in England and
Wales, decided to relocate its head offices from London to Bristol in
October 1989 at an estimated cost of Pounds 1m.
To save time the NRA, without the chief executive's knowledge, decided to
negotiate a contract with Corporate Design and Construct (CDC) rather than
putting it out for tender. The National Audit Office report also shows how
costs rose, without the board's approval, to Pounds 2.65m.
The NRA's internal inquiry found tendering and contractual failings and weak
financial controls and procedures. It encouraged CDC to ensure that Pounds
1.4m was spent on the project by March 31 last year in order to prevent the
loss of any government grants unspent before the end of the financial year.
</TEXT>
