<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JAN 92 / Falls in construction orders point to continued recession
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DEEP recession in the construction industry shows little sign of
abating, according to figures published yesterday by the environment
department that show a further fall in contractors' order books.
The department said the value of construction orders at constant 1985 prices
during the three months to the end of November fell by 6 per cent compared
with the corresponding period last year, and by 5 per cent compared with the
previous three months.
Orders at the end of the first 11 months of last year were more than a tenth
lower than during the same period in 1990 and almost a quarter down on that
period in 1989.
Mr John Smith, president of the Building Employers Confederation, said on
Monday that competition for work meant that at least half of building
contracts won recently were either loss-making or had a zero margin. He
warned that construction output was expected to fall by about 5 per cent
this year to the lowest level since 1986, and was likely to lead to the loss
of a further 50,000 jobs.
Mr Tim Yeo, environment minister, said the order figures for the period from
July to November showed an increase in housing and industrial orders on the
corresponding period in 1990. 'I welcome this latest evidence that orders in
much of the construction industry are showing signs of recovery,' he said.
Miss Joanne Cutler, economist at the confederation, said Mr Yeo's comments
on recovery conflicted with what companies were telling her organisation.
The environment department's most recent figures, for September, October and
November, showed that orders compared with the corresponding period in 1990
were falling or flat in every sector except public housing, she said.
According to the department, private industrial orders were 16 per cent
lower than during June, July and August and 8 per cent lower than during the
corresponding period in 1990.
Private commercial orders were 6 per cent and 15 per cent lower
respectively.
Private housing orders were 18 per cent lower than during the previous three
months, but 1 per cent higher than during September, October and November in
1990. Public housing orders including housing associations were 8 per cent
and 141 per cent higher.
Orders for public works other than housing were 14 per cent higher than
during the previous three months, but 7 per cent lower than a year earlier.
British brick manufacturers last year sold 3.1bn bricks, the lowest annual
deliveries since records started in 1968.
Figures published yesterday by the environment department show that the
number of unsold bricks at the end of last year stood at a record 1.4bn.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
